a vow to myself, for 2023.

I vow to continue loving and accepting myself, all and every part of me, physically and mentally, even more than I did in 2022.

I vow to be vulnerable and to stay open to changes and opportunities, even after times I get hurt.

I vow to not neglect my own needs and to set boundaries with myself and others. 

I vow to love wholeheartedly and be fully present, whether that’s with people, places, or moments - no matter how big or small. 

I vow to be my own best friend. I vow to be someone I am proud of.

I vow to be kind to myself, in any phase I’m going through to become the person I’m meant to be. I vow to embrace every step, whether happy or sad, along the way.

I vow to not give others the power or control over me and my emotions. I vow to take charge of my own life. 

I vow to acknowledge the beauty reflected back to me in the mirror and to not stand there to pick out my flaws. 

I vow to be shamelessly me and unapologetically human in everything I do.

I vow to forgive myself for all the mistakes I am bound to make and to continue forgiving myself for the ones I have already made. 

I vow to follow my dreams no matter how big or time consuming they are. 

I vow to continue traveling, exploring, and discovering new places and new parts of myself.

back to work 💅🏼⁣
⁣
due to traveling and being sick a bit around Christmas, it’s been about 3ish weeks since I’ve fully followed my workout program and tracked food - but now we’re back baby. I plan on easing back into everything slowly, to find my routine and to find my strength again. ⁣
⁣
next week I head back to work and start my first busy season and let me just say.. I’m quite nervous, mainly because I know it’ll probably take a toll on my mental health (and maybe physical) with the long and tiring work hours. however, I do have some goals for the next two months to try my best to get through it:⁣
⁣
🍓 be strict about my night routine & bed time to at least get 7.5-8 hours of sleep per night ⁣
⁣
🍓 complete all of my workouts each week, or at least 4 out of 5 of them, and then to also make time to workout or do some kind of exercise if I have to travel to San Fran for work⁣
⁣
🍓 focus on my water intake and getting up often to stretch during the work day, so I’m not just sitting/staring at my computer for hours on end⁣
⁣
🍓 make time for both self care/alone time as well as socialization to see friends at least once a week⁣
⁣
🍓 cook & prep meals/ingredients on the weekends to save both time & money bc I know I’ll be too lazy during the week to cook⁣
⁣
here’s to staying disciplined & staying on top of my shit 🫡
enjoying where I am now, but working to get to where I want to be.

if you want it, then work for i⁣t.

this is your reminder to forgive yourself..⁣
⁣
forgive yourself for the way you treated yourself in the past.⁣
⁣
forgive yourself for the way you talked to your body.⁣
⁣
forgive yourself for the way you held yourself back because you didn’t believe in your own potential, because you didn’t believe in your capacity to take up space.⁣
⁣
forgive yourself for all the things you didn’t say, didn’t wear, or didn’t do because you were afraid of how it would make you look or how others may look at you.⁣
⁣
forgive yourself for the survival patterns and traits you picked up while enduring trauma.⁣
⁣
forgive yourself for giving away your power and for  settling for less than you wanted or knew you needed, because you didn’t think you deserved it. ⁣
⁣
forgive yourself for the way you held yourself back and for the ways in which you didn’t see just how worthy you are. ⁣

you are worthy, you are beautiful, and you are human. we make mistakes and that’s okay. the way you love others and forgive others is how you should love and forgive yourself. you deserve to take up all the space and allow yourself to become the person you want to be, who you’re meant to be.

let me get real with y’all - I took the first picture this morning and thought “wow, look at my quads!!” and I genuinely just felt so proud of myself and of my progress - but then I remember just yesterday that I sent the second picture to my coach and was talking about how insecure and unconfident I was feeling with how my body was looking. ⁣
⁣
body dysmorphia can be such a bitch sometimes and it can come in waves, some days I feel so good and the others I feel completely opposite and I just want to pick out all my flaws. my coach and I knew this difficult mental battle was going to come to surface and stick around once I started bulking, but I truly don’t think I could have a better coach to walk me through it and support me.⁣
⁣
some things he’s told me that I think is important to share in case anyone else needs to hear them:⁣
⁣
• I will always be my own worst critic⁣
• the version of myself that I see and the version of myself that others see are two totally different things⁣
• people are in my life and love me for who I am because of my personality and character, not for what I look like⁣
⁣
he also recommended me to go through pics and to highlight the qualities I love about myself and are proud of - so the rest of the pics/videos are just that. I am proud of how much stronger I’ve gotten over the last couple months. I’m proud of how defined my hamstrings got. I’m proud of my glute growth. I’m proud of the weight I’ve been able to push on upper body days.

ditch your comfort zone. ⁣

Ever since the skiing accident when I tore my ACL, I have felt just about every emotion imaginable. I felt scared, scared because this is my first major injury and my first major surgery. I felt mad, and doubtful, and lost - mad at myself for this happening, mad at my body for hurting all the time and being so limited in my daily activities like not being able to walk winter or get into the shower as easy, and mad at the world because this messed up so many of my plans. I’ve felt embarrassed and felt like a burden, since I can’t do things as easily and I need to ask for assistance for just about everything. I’ve constantly felt lonely since I’ve spent so much time just sitting alone and I constantly get upset with myself for being so far away from my family and their help. However, I’ve felt grateful - grateful that this accident wasn’t worse, grateful to have been able to walk away (even if it was with crutches), and grateful this pain is only temporary. I’m hopeful, for what’s to come and for the journey that lies ahead because I know it can only go up from here. And I’m proud, proud of my body for being so amazing and strong because I know I will heal and I will recover from this and become only stronger, both mentally and physically. And I am oh so appreciative of all the help and the kindness I’ve received from friends here, although I haven’t lived here long. 

So no matter how much I get dragged down, no matter how many bad days I may encounter, I will keep moving forward. I will keep pushing and I will keep trying. I will feel all my emotions, the good and the bad, and take on each new day as it comes. Even if I doubt myself sometimes, I know I will get through this.

one week post ACL reconstruction & meniscus repair ⁣🩼
⁣
I am.. okay ish.. This past week has been hard, mentally and physically. The pain was awful, especially the first few days after the surgery but now it’s getting to be a bit more bearable. I’ve been constantly on the verge of tears, crying almost every day due to the pain, for not being as mobile and independent as I want to be, because I feel like I’m missing out on life, and for so many other reasons. ⁣
⁣
But on the positive side of things, I finished my second PT session this morning and am now headed down to TX for the next two weeks so I could get some more reliable help with myself and winter while I’m still on crutches and not allowed to bear any weight on my left leg. At PT, I was able  to get my leg fully straight to 0 degrees and was able to bend it 90 degrees, which is good progress so far. ⁣
⁣
Day by day, things are getting better, slowly but surely on this road to recovery.

hello from me n my new knee 🤠💫🐙⁣
⁣
doctor cleared me to finally bear weight on my leg so now I’m relearning how to walk, which is uh.. weird. I feel like a newborn baby deer if I’m being honest lol 🦌⁣
⁣
I’ll still be on crutches for a little while until some strength is back but I am now able to (as of today per PT orders) ride the stationary bike and go to the gym and do some upper body 🥳🤭😼⁣
⁣
some other progress since my surgery 3 weeks ago:⁣
• my range of motion has now surpassed 130 degrees⁣
• today I did my first unassisted straight leg lift! it was the last rep of my set and it didn’t feel the greatest but I still did it on my own!

back day bc ya girl is back in the gym 😽⁣
⁣
3.5 weeks post ACL reconstruction / meniscus repair and I am back to finally working out and moving my body some! I’ll be working with light weights and slow reps for a bit to regain my strength and to find my muscle memory again. my workouts will consist of modified upper body workouts for a while until I can put full weight onto my left leg to do standing movements - and then once I’m good there, all upper body movements will be game 🥵⁣
⁣
I’m still not 100% walking on my own yet, but I trust my body and its ability to recover. I’ll be moving so smoothly in no time, and leg days will come back sooner than later I already know it. ⁣
⁣
@thetransformgym

feelin’ like a brand new woman because I can finally walk again!!⁣
⁣
after 6 weeks of crutches and 3 of those weeks being non weight bearing, I can finally say bye bye to both of my crutches 🤑✌🏼⁣
⁣
I’ve still got a slight limp in my walk but my leg is strong enough to not need anymore assistance 💅🏼⁣
⁣
the last couple days have been emotional (but a good emotional) with walking again, going back to the gym, and being able to get into the office again.. I feel like I’m starting to slowly rebuild and regain my life back and it just makes me so happy 🥹 I’m so excited to see what’s in store the next couple months and to see how much more I’ll be able to do!

no leg day, no problem. upper body’s bout to be HUGE 🫡⁣⁣
⁣⁣
I am sad about no leg days for a while and having lost most of my muscle in my left leg, but I find that setting some goals for myself like this helps me stay inspired and disciplined. It makes me excited to continue going to the gym and pushes me to keep showing up each day, even if I feel restricted/limited mentally. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
even if my body isn’t at 100%, it’s still so damn capable and strong. ⁣
⁣

just because it’s taking time doesn’t mean it’s not happening. ⁣
⁣
💫 🦋 🧚‍♂️🌈🫧⁣
⁣
I would find myself constantly getting upset or feeling defeated or doubting myself, because I’m not as recovered as I’d like to be, or because my knee still hurts going up stairs or doing other rehab exercises - but at the end of the day, I have to remind myself that it takes time and that I’ve progressed so much already. today I am 7 weeks post op and I’m out walking, and doing lunges again, and gaining my independence back, which felt like it was a lifetime away just a month ago.⁣
⁣
 looking back and reflecting over my recovery so far, I know I’m making progress, even if it’s just tiny baby steps each day and each week. & to be completely honest, my mental health during this whole journey isn’t going to be amazing and perfect - and I will constantly have moments like today - but I think it’s so important to realize that when I do start getting down on myself, I just need to take a step back and reflect.. and truly realize how far I’ve really come since the beginning of this all.

flowing, not forcing.⁣
⁣
accepting what life may throw at me, learning to love every bit of the process, and expressing gratitude for all the small moments happening each and every day. ⁣
⁣
even if it’s a bad day, it’s not a bad life. ⁣
⁣
🌙🍯🐝💛💐

𝐦𝐚𝐲 𝐧𝐨𝐭𝐞𝐬 & 𝐠𝐫𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐭𝐮𝐝𝐞:⁣
⁣
this week I’ve hit 9 weeks post op!! this time last month, I was feeling so uneasy in my walk with a slight limp and some pain in each step, but now walking feels completely normal about 95% of the time! ⁣
⁣
I’ve been able to gain so much of my independence and life back over this month - like just being able to take winter on walks that are a mile or two long again and being able to go into the gym and do some simple leg movements (even if that’s just being able to bodyweight squat or do the leg press machine with not added weight) - these may seem so small to some but they were HUGE achievements for me this month, esp with them being activities that were (and are) such big parts of my life that were taken away for like two months ⁣
⁣
I stayed open, and will stay open, to opportunities and possibilities in the romantic/dating area of my life, no matter what I may have faced this month. I have the right people in my life right now to show me I am worthy and that I don’t deserve to settle, even at moments I may feel lonely. ⁣
⁣
some things I am grateful for from this month:⁣
🍬being able to go home this past weekend but especially for when my 7 y/o niece yelled ‘aunt Kelsey’ & jumped into my arms when surprising her at her house, having my 5 y/o nephew cuddle with me on the couch after a long river day, having both the two youngest babies jump into my arms in the pool & seeing them laugh & smile each time, and for the giggles and smirks when talking about boys with the oldest niece⁣
🍬the game night and dinner date with my friends⁣
🍬being able to travel to SF for work & getting the chance to make memories with my team⁣
🍬getting to dress cute for spring and wear fun sundresses for no reason⁣
🍬being able to try new places and things (new coffee places, restaurants, going golfing, etc)⁣

today I hit 12 weeks post ACL reconstruction & meniscus repair!! this past weekend I hit another milestone as it was my first time driving back into the mountains since my skiing accident in march - even though it was for a very easy & short hike with no rocks or elevation changes, it is still a milestone mentally!⁣
⁣
about two weeks ago I did have a set back in my recovery that affected my mental health quite bad. my PT exercises were limited to things I was doing about a month in, due to me overdoing some movements that caused my knee a lot of discomfort which made it swell up for about a week. however, most of the swelling has gone down now and it looks like I can start getting back into squats and Bulgarian split squats like I was doing before this road block (hopefully lol, depending on how PT goes today).⁣
⁣
although I feel dumb for causing myself to have this set back, I know the road to recovery isn’t always going to be a straight linear path, so I need to give myself grace through it all. it’s difficult, but I’m trying. every day is another day to improve and get better.⁣
⁣

I miss my quads but at least I still kinda have my hamstrings? right? 🤨🫠🤧⁣

if I’m being honest, this whole journey of recovery has been kickin my asssss lately 🫥 mentally I just feel so defeated and I feel like it’s taking forever for my knee to heal - especially when one day I’ll be walking with ease and no pain and the next I can’t even do a set of 10 of body weight squats or lunges without slight pain or discomfort. ⁣
⁣
everyday is a different mental battle, and I keep showing up for myself but omg I’m really fighting it sometimes. I will not give up on myself, but don’t get me wrong.. those thoughts have crossed my mind at times but I don’t let them stick. this may be a set back, but deep down I know it’s not permanent. I will get through it, no matter how hard it may get or how much I may beat myself up about it. I will heal. I will recover. ⁣
⁣

went to a commercial gym the other day for the first time in over a year..⁣
⁣
was I nervous? yes. did I feel my gym anxiety come back? sadly, yes.⁣
⁣
even after almost 5 years of working out and joining many different gyms, my gym anxiety still exists and is still something I continue to work on. honestly, there’s even days I’m at my private gym and I start to feel that anxiety (mainly when I see one too many cars in the parking lot.. the worst)⁣
⁣
things I do to help ease that anxiety:⁣
⁣
1. go with a friend 👯‍♀️ I tried to go with one of my friends on Tuesday but the timing just didn’t work out since I needed to go so early, but fortunately as I was warming up, I noticed one of my coworkers across the turf and it made me feel soooo much more comfortable knowing at least one person there.⁣
⁣
2. turn up your best playlist and try not to look around 🫢 I find myself getting more nervous about other people possibly watching me or judging me when I’m staring off across the gym and randomly catch someone’s eye.. so I’ve found that by keeping my gaze on what I’m doing or zoning out on something next to me allows me to tune all that out and keep those “are the looking at me and judging me??” thoughts out of my head ⁣
⁣
3. this is cliche but wear something you feel good in. 💅🏼 when I wear a cute fit that makes me feel good, I tend to just focus on myself and not others - like who cares what someone else may think bc I left my house feelin SO good and SO cute, and at the end of the day, my opinion is what matters. (taking pre workout also helps intensify this feeling tbh) ⁣
⁣
⁣
if you’ve ever felt gym anxiety and/or nervousness when trying out a new gym or even your normal everyday gym, you are not alone, I promise.

daily reminder, for myself and anyone else who needs it 🫶🏻⁣

everyone you see in the gym is at a different stage in their life and phase in their journey. your programs will look different, your approaches will look different, your physiques will look different, and your goals will look different - and that is okay. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
it is okay to have different goals than the person next to you.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
it is okay to look different than the person next to you.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
it is okay to be on a different journey or a different phase of a similar journey than the person next to you. ⁣
⁣
you are your only competition, not that girl or guy you see across the gym.⁣ ⁣
⁣
it’s you vs. you.

in two days I’ll hit 8 months post ACL/meniscus surgery and I’m honestly feelin goooood. I jumped again for the first time back in October and this past week I jogged for the first time! and today I used the pendulum squat at my gym for the very first time 🥹 (big s/o to @randaldean24 for the help & guidance)⁣
⁣
todays workout:⁣
- warm up on the bike ⁣
- jumping drills (frog hops front and back, ladder drills, runner hops)⁣
- treadmill jogging (walk .1 and jog .1 until 2 miles)⁣
- strength training (leg press, db RDLs, smith machine squats, leg extensions - all low weight, no extra weight added to machines)⁣
⁣
every day, especially the days I do PT exercises, it’s a huge mental battle to push myself past my fears and do things that feel out of my reach. I constantly doubt myself and my knee, but today my goal was to push aside those doubts and to try new and hard things - like the running drill and the pendulum squat… and I did just that. I’m not where I want to be of course, but today was a good today - a day of progress and a day of growth - and for that, I am SO proud of myself. 🩷🩷🩷⁣
⁣

push up pr!! 😼😼⁣
⁣
push ups have always been something I’ve struggled with, due to a past shoulder/collar bone injury back in 2019 and due to not enough practice. when I started up beginner calisthenics workouts a few months ago, I was determined to practice my push ups no matter where or when so I could get better at them. the last time I did them, I did 8 … and this time 10!! I did feel like I maybe could’ve gone down more, so I did another set of 6 where I tried to go down just an inch further. ⁣(all tips and advice on form are appreciated 😘)
⁣
whatever it is, you have to keep trying and keep pushing (literally) if you want to get better at it. I hate saying that practice makes perfect, bc what is perfect? BUT practice definitely makes improvement. 🥳⁣
⁣

this movement is called ‘skin the cat.’ I actually used to do these a lot on my home playground as a grew up without even realizing it. so today I went in with the mindset like “oh yeah I’ve done these before, just on rings, a bar won’t be much different. I can do it” I was wrong 😵‍💫 what I didn’t realize is that I’ve always done them sooo close to the ground, the rings on my playground were maybe like 4 feet in the air?? so I would just flip back and forth, with my feet touching the ground each time. the bar at my gym is not crazy high but felt like I was SO high when I flipped over. ⁣

one surgical leg and many tattoos later… we’re back to deadlifting!!!⁣
⁣
⁣
after 8.5 months of post op, my PT said I can finally do heavy weightlifting again 🥹🥹⁣
⁣
I started off with my brace just so my knee could feel stable and comfortable being in the sumo position, since it hasn’t done that since March, and then removed it so I could focus on my technique and the bar being up against my shins. To be honest, it definitely felt strange and weird physically to do this movement again but mentally, gosh it felt SO good to be back. ⁣
⁣
I video’d myself from the back to watch my form and while coming back down, I noticed a small shift in my hips. This shift has been recurring in a lot of my movements (squats, jumps, etc) since I don’t have full strength back in my left leg, so I know this will be fixed in time. However, I wanna really focus on fixing this in this 65lb deadlift before trying to go up in weight. It’ll be a while until I hit some big numbers again, but I’ll get back to that one day. I just have to trust the process. ⁣
⁣
